SOC (Security Operations Center)

SOC Analyst Tiers
| Tier | Role |

| Tier 1 | Alert triage — monitor SIEM, initial response |
| Tier 2 | Incident handling — deeper investigation |
| Tier 3 | Threat hunting — proactive, advanced analysis |
| Lead | Management, strategy, escalation |

What SOC Monitors
- Network traffic anomalies
- Failed login attempts / brute force
- Malware detections (AV/EDR)
- Unauthorized access attempts
- Lateral movement indicators

---
SIEM (Security Information & Event Management)

Purpose: Aggregate logs → correlate events → alert on threats

Examples: Splunk, Microsoft Sentinel, IBM QRadar, Elastic SIEM

 Basic Splunk Query Syntax

index=* sourcetype=syslog "failed password"
index=* src_ip=192.168.1.* | stats count by dest_ip
index=* EventCode=4625    # Failed Windows logon

---
IDS vs IPS

| | IDS | IPS |

| Action | Detects & alerts | Detects & blocks |
| Placement | Passive (out of band) | Inline |
| Risk | No blocking = attacker can proceed | False positives can block legit traffic |
| Example | Snort (IDS mode) | Snort (IPS mode), Suricata |

---
Incident Response (IR) — NIST Framework


1. PREPARATION    → Policies, playbooks, tools, training
2. DETECTION      → Alerts, logs, SIEM, user reports
3. CONTAINMENT    → Isolate affected systems (short-term + long-term)
4. ERADICATION    → Remove malware, patch vulnerability
5. RECOVERY       → Restore systems, monitor
6. LESSONS LEARNED → Post-incident report, improve


